It works for me. Make sure to have the Bean3 in the context, for instances by using `Component` annotation.

    @Component
    public class Bean3 {}

No, you don&#39;t have circular dependency the case which you defined. As mentioned by @Andreas, this is one way of dependency not circular.

The circular is dependency is like, 

    @Configuration
    public class Bean2 {
    
      @Autowired
      private Bean3 bean3;

    }

And

    @Configuration
    public class Bean3 {
    
      @Autowired
      private Bean2 bean2;
    }

This kind of example is of type of circular dependency.

There are ways to avoid this, like using of @Autowire on setter method of the object or use @Lazy on object. By this one object is created at the time of application loading and one is at the time of requirement.

Hope this help.

