Two things you can try. First, I don&#39;t think `.click()` is an option on `ElementArrayFinder` objects. That&#39;s what you get when you use `element.all()`. You need to get a specific button out of the list to click on. You can use `.first()`, `.last()`, or `.get(index)` to accomplish this. First and last are pretty self explanatory. Lets say you have 4 of these buttons and you want to click on the third one, it would be:

    element.all(by.id(&#39;next&#39;)).get(2).click();

I understand from your comments that you have a next button on multiple pages. If there is only one button on each page, you can most likely get away with just using `element(by.id(&#39;next&#39;))` instead of `element.all()`. Unless all of those other next buttons are still present in the DOM when you advance to a new page you shouldn&#39;t need to use `element.all()`.

Second option is to add a function that uses `ExpectedCondition.elementToBeClickable()` and wait for the button to be clickable before you try to click on it. 

    public EC = ExpectedConditions;

    public async waitForElementToBeClickable(element: ElementFinder): Promise&lt;void&gt; {
      await browser.wait(this.EC.elementToBeClickable(element), this.wait);
    }

Wherever you want to click on the button you would just do it like this:

    const nextButtons = element.all(by.id(&#39;next&#39;));

    await waitForElementToBeClickable(nextButtons.first());
    await nextButtons.first().click();

Answer to your question &quot;How to click a button multilple times with the same element id in the same page&quot;

```
